            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mei Hadzic\u2019s life is a study in precision, a trait honed by both her upbringing and her profession. Born Mei Lin to Taiwanese immigrants in San Jose, her childhood was steeped in the expectation of academic excellence. Her parents, a software engineer and a lab technician, saw education as the unwavering path to stability, and Mei, with her quiet diligence, did not disappoint. She excelled in the sciences, finding a natural elegance in the complex systems of biology.\n\nHer educational journey took her north, first to UC Davis for her undergraduate degree and then to UCSF for her PhD in Pharmacology. It was in the demanding environment of graduate school that her life took its most significant turn. She met Adnan Hadzic, a brilliant and impossibly charming post-doctoral fellow in a neighboring lab. A refugee from the Bosnian War, his resilience and expansive worldview captivated Mei, pulling her out of her academic shell. They married shortly after she completed her doctorate, and she proudly took his name, a fusion of their two disparate, yet complementary, worlds.\n\nThey built a life in the Bay Area\u2019s burgeoning biotech scene. Mei methodically climbed the ladder from bench scientist to project manager. Their shared dream was cut short a decade ago when Adnan was diagnosed with an aggressive, fast-moving cancer. His death reshaped Mei\u2019s world. Her work, once a professional pursuit, became a deeply personal crusade. Grief fueled a new, sharper focus, and she channeled her energy into her career, accepting a Director position overseeing complex clinical trials.\n\nNow, at 48, Mei lives a life of disciplined routine in a quiet Potrero Hill condo. Her days begin before dawn with a cup of oolong tea and a review of global trial data. The 28-Holland bus is her mobile office, a 2.8-mile commute to Mission Bay where she manages international teams, multi-million dollar budgets, and the fragile hopes of patients. Evenings are for unwinding\u2014either by cooking the intricate Taiwanese dishes of her youth or taking long, steep walks through her neighborhood, admiring the city lights. While content in her focused independence, she holds a quiet aspiration to one day see another drug shepherded through trials become a standard of care, a tangible legacy of her life\u2019s work. San Francisco is no longer just a place of opportunity; it is the city that holds her entire history\u2014her education, her career, her great love, and her profound loss."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers him leaning against her lab-bench door at UCSF, interrupting her titration with a terrible pun about pipettes. Adnan, the post-doc from next door, with his war-torn past and an easy, dazzling smile. Mei felt a flash of annoyance at the disruption, but then he\u2019d just *looked* at her, seeing past the lab coat and the data. Twenty-two years ago, that moment cracked open her carefully constructed world. It was the first time she realized a precise life could still have room for beautiful, wonderful chaos.\n\n2.\nAt City Hall, the clerk stumbled over \"Hadzic.\" Adnan just laughed his big, booming laugh. For Mei, choosing his name wasn't about tradition; it was a declaration. It was fusing her ordered world of Lin with his resilient one. She pictured their names on a mailbox, a molecule of two disparate elements bonding into something stronger. She was 29, holding a marriage certificate that felt like a blueprint for their entire future. For the first time, she felt completely, indivisibly whole.\n\n3.\nThey used to walk the crest of Potrero Hill on clear nights, sharing a thermos of the too-sweet tea he insisted on making. About fifteen years ago, he\u2019d stopped her mid-sentence about a protocol flaw. \u201cMei, look,\u201d he said, pointing not at the skyline but up, at the faint stars. \u201cWe\u2019re so small, isn\u2019t it wonderful?\u201d The memory is a constant companion on her evening walks now, a quiet ache of a time when the universe felt expansive and kind, not clinical and cruel.\n\n4.\nTen years ago, in a sterile consultation room, the oncologist spoke in terms she understood perfectly\u2014unresponsive tumors, aggressive metastatic pathways. Her PhD, her life's work, was useless. Adnan squeezed her hand, his palpable strength a stark contrast to the cellular betrayal within him. It was the moment science, her lifelong sanctuary of logic, became personal. Grief was a cold, sharp thing, and in that room, it crystallized inside her, forging the harder, more focused purpose she now carries every day.\n\n5.\nIt was three years after Adnan\u2019s death. The positive phase II data for an oncology drug materialized on her screen late one night. She didn\u2019t feel elation, but a profound, gut-wrenching relief. Each data point was a family that might be spared what she endured. Staring at the glowing monitor in her silent Mission Bay office, she whispered his name. This was her new language of love, spoken in datasets and protocols\u2014a tangible legacy built from the ashes of her own."
